[{"id":"VR871126","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows an energy level diagram of an atom. The diagram has three levels. The top level is E sub 0, and n equals 3. The second level is 0.8 E sub 0, and n equals 2. The third level is 0, and n equals 1.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR871126.g02.svg\"/></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The diagram shows the energy levels of a hypothetical atom, with the energy levels given in terms of a constant <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E sub 0\"><math alttext=\"E sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>. From all the possible photons that can be emitted by the atom, does the transition between levels <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n equals 2\"><math alttext=\"n equals 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>n</mi><mo> </mo><mo>=</mo><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n equals 3\"><math alttext=\"n equals 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>n</mi><mo> </mo><mo>=</mo><mo> </mo><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> result in the emission of a photon with the longest wavelength or shortest wavelength? What is the justification?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR871126_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The longest wavelength, because levels <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> are the highest-energy levels in the atom.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The longest wavelength, because levels <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> have the smallest energy difference between any pair of levels.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The shortest wavelength, because levels <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> are the highest-energy levels in the atom.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The shortest wavelength, because levels <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> have the smallest energy difference between any pair of levels.</p>"],"answer":1}]